                           <div style="" tabindex="0">
                            <a class="tap-target update-components-mini-update-v2__link-to-details-page text-body-medium ember-view" href="/feed/update/urn:li:activity:7294207978004512768/" id="ember110" tabindex="-1">
                             <div class="feed-shared-inline-show-more-text feed-shared-update-v2__description feed-shared-inline-show-more-text--minimal-padding feed-shared-inline-show-more-text--8-lines" tabindex="-1">
                              <div class="update-components-text relative update-components-update-v2__commentary" dir="ltr">
                               <!-- -->
                               <span class="break-words tvm-parent-container">
                                <!-- -->
                                <span dir="ltr">
                                 <!-- -->
                                 NIH has just announced that it will save $4 billion by capping university indirect costs on federal grants. Will this actually save money?
                                 <span class="white-space-pre">
                                 </span>
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <!-- -->
                                 Bottom line: No. It will probably cost a lot more than it saves. Here's why: Imagine if every researcher had to spend their time figuring out how to pay for internet, phone, real estate, janitorial services, writing budgets, security services, and verifying compliance with HR and other administrative requirements, instead of having the university do it.  This is a terrible use of our most talented scientists' time.
                                 <!-- -->
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <!-- -->
                                 Here's an FAQ:
                                 <!-- -->
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <!-- -->
                                 Q: What are "indirect costs" in university research funding?
                                 <!-- -->
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <!-- -->
                                 A: Indirect costs cover essential expenses that support research but arent tied to one specific project. This includes lab space, utilities, security, internet, and staff who handle grant paperwork and safety compliance.
                                 <span class="white-space-pre">
                                 </span>
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <!-- -->
                                 Q: What happens if these costs are capped at 15% for all universities?
                                 <!-- -->
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <!-- -->
                                 A: Universities will have less money to maintain research labs, pay staff, and follow federal safety rules. This could slow down scientific breakthroughs, reduce job opportunities, and hurt the economy.
                                 <!-- -->
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <!-- -->
                                 Q: How would this affect medical and technology research?
                                 <!-- -->
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <!-- -->
                                 A: Many medical discoveries and tech innovations come from university research. Cuts could delay new treatments for diseases, slow down clean energy development, and hurt industries like AI and biotech.
                                 <!-- -->
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <!-- -->
                                 Q: Wont universities just cover the difference?
                                 <!-- -->
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <!-- -->
                                 A: Many public universities, especially smaller ones, cant afford to. They might cut research programs, increase tuition, or reduce student opportunities. Overall, the U.S. research system would weaken and more burden would fall on individual researchers to do administrative work instead of science.
                                 <!-- -->
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <!-- -->
                                 Q: Would this hurt students?
                                 <!-- -->
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <!-- -->
                                 A: Yes. Fewer research grants mean fewer hands-on learning opportunities for students. It could also reduce scholarships and make it harder for graduates to find high-paying jobs in science and technology.
                                 <!-- -->
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <!-- -->
                                 Q: How would this affect jobs?
                                 <!-- -->
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <!-- -->
                                 A: Universities might lay off research staff, reducing jobs in labs, IT, and administration. It could also slow job growth in industries that rely on university research, like healthcare, engineering, and cybersecurity.
                                 <!-- -->
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <!-- -->
                                 Q: Whats the big picture?
                                 <!-- -->
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <!-- -->
                                 A: A 15% cap on indirect costs will weaken Americas leadership in science and innovation. Other countries are investing more in researchif we cut back, we risk falling behind in medicine, technology, and global competitiveness.
                                 <!-- -->
                                </span>
                               </span>
                              </div>

                                more

                            <a class="tap-target update-components-mini-update-v2__link-to-details-page text-body-medium ember-view" href="/feed/update/urn:li:activity:7284658097824890881/" id="ember186" tabindex="-1">
                             <div class="feed-shared-inline-show-more-text feed-shared-update-v2__description feed-shared-inline-show-more-text--minimal-padding feed-shared-inline-show-more-text--2-lines" tabindex="-1">
                              <div class="update-components-text relative update-components-update-v2__commentary" dir="ltr">
                               <!-- -->
                               <span class="break-words tvm-parent-container">
                                <!-- -->
                                <span dir="ltr">
                                 <!-- -->
                                 Why I Left HR to Pursue a PhD  and How It Transformed My Career
                                 <!-- -->
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <!-- -->
                                 Twenty years ago, I made the decision to leave my career in HR and embark on the journey of earning a PhD. It wasnt an easy choice, but it was the right one for me. Heres why:
                                 <!-- -->
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <!-- -->
                                 1 Strategic Thinking &amp; Lifelong Learning
                                 <!-- -->
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <!-- -->
                                 Ive always been curious and drawn to big-picture thinking. I loved digging deep into problems, asking why, and figuring out how to align strategy with people and processes. A PhD allowed me to channel that curiosity into research and deeper understanding.
                                 <!-- -->
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <!-- -->
                                 2 Mentorship
                                 <!-- -->
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <!-- -->
                                 I was passionate about mentoring and wanted to guide the next generation of HR and management professionals. Academia offered me the opportunity to teach and inspire college studentshelping them prepare for careers and make meaningful contributions to the field.
                                 <!-- -->
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <!-- -->
                                 3 Bridging Academia &amp; Industry
                                 <!-- -->
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <!-- -->
                                 One of my favorite aspects of this journey has been finding ways to connect what I learn through research with the realities I experienced in HR. Its a win-winpractitioners gain insights from rigorous research, and academia benefits from industry relevance.
                                 <!-- -->
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <!-- -->
                                 Looking back, if an Executive PhD program had been an option back then, I would have jumped at the chance. Programs like Clemson Universitys Executive Leadership PhD in the Management Department offer the flexibility to balance work and study while providing the tools to excel in academia, consulting, or industry. This degree empowers leaders to tackle real-world problems with data-driven insightsnot just follow benchmarks.
                                 <!-- -->
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <!-- -->
                                 If any of this resonates with you, I encourage you to explore Clemson Universitys Executive Leadership PhD program. It might just be the next step in your career journey:
                                 <span class="white-space-pre">
                                 </span>
                                 <a class="RFNOFVQEFZPHaKoCyqsqedOluNQlOEMFjaDeg" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://lnkd.in/eJWAzxAe" tabindex="0" target="_self">
                                  <!-- -->
                                  https://lnkd.in/eJWAzxAe
                                  <!-- -->
                                 </a>
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <!-- -->
                                 Lets keep learning, growing, and making an impactwherever we are.
                                 <!-- -->
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <span>
                                  <br/>
                                 </span>
                                 <a class="RFNOFVQEFZPHaKoCyqsqedOluNQlOEMFjaDeg" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/feed/hashtag/?keywords=executivephd&amp;highlightedUpdateUrns=urn%3Ali%3Aactivity%3A7285264860819410944" tabindex="0">

                                  <span class="visually-hidden">

                               <span dir="ltr">
                                <!-- -->
                                Linkages between technology, innovation, and entrepreneurship have materially impacted markets, societies, and environmentsin good, bad, and undetermined ways. In the spirit of better understanding these linkages and impacts, colleagues
                                <span class="white-space-pre">
                                </span>
                                <a class="RFNOFVQEFZPHaKoCyqsqedOluNQlOEMFjaDeg" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/ACoAAAbvsoIB3ap9dykcuVaWLhlJO3PBmSTxSVY" tabindex="0" target="_self">
                                 <span>
                                  <a class="ember-view" href="/in/guerreromaribel/" id="ember895">
                                   <!-- -->
                                   Maribel Guerrero
                                   <!-- -->
                                  </a>
                                 </span>
                                </a>
                                <!-- -->
                                ,
                                <span class="white-space-pre">
                                </span>
                                <a class="RFNOFVQEFZPHaKoCyqsqedOluNQlOEMFjaDeg" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/ACoAAAlD9w8Bde_HNx8gBnSMIqdLCMCGeXWOrZ8" tabindex="0" target="_self">
                                 <span>
                                  <a class="ember-view" href="/in/donald-siegel-b7b08644/" id="ember896">
                                   <!-- -->

                                  <a class="ember-view" href="/in/chad-navis-603413/" id="ember897">

                                , and I enthusiastically solicit submissions for special issue of
                                <span class="white-space-pre">
                                </span>
                                <a class="RFNOFVQEFZPHaKoCyqsqedOluNQlOEMFjaDeg" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/company/journal-of-business-venturing/" tabindex="0" target="_self">

                                (see shared post below). If you are doing research in this space, using any theoretical lens at any level of analysis, we would love to learn about your ideas and consider them for publication. We welcome theoretical, qualitative, quantitative, and mixed method work that pushes the boundaries of entrepreneurship research in bold and rigorous ways!

                                </span>
                                Entrepreneurship and Family Business study abroad students toured Pamplona yesterday! The students learned about the Running of the Bulls, Navarres regional economy, and the entrepreneurial spirit of the area. Seeing this group grow their independence and foster their entrepreneurial mindset has been a highlight of this trip for me. Super proud of this group!

                               <span dir="ltr">
                                <!-- -->
                                Next up on Clemson's Entrepreneurship and Family Business in Spain study abroad program was Madrid. Special thanks to
                                <span class="white-space-pre">
                                </span>
                                <a class="RFNOFVQEFZPHaKoCyqsqedOluNQlOEMFjaDeg" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/ACoAAADsZksBmQjqYmkjTpNzZ-6k18IMej0SBjQ" tabindex="0" target="_self">
                                 <span>
                                  <a class="ember-view" href="/in/ckyprianou/" id="ember676">
                                   <!-- -->
                                   Christina Kyprianou
                                   <!-- -->
                                  </a>
                                 </span>
                                </a>
                                <!-- -->
                                , a former entrepreneurship professor at Clemson, who organized a fantastic visit for our group to IE Madrid this past Friday, where she and
                                <span class="white-space-pre">
                                </span>
                                <a class="RFNOFVQEFZPHaKoCyqsqedOluNQlOEMFjaDeg" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/ACoAAAAxA9kBHL3jgBqq23o0SXQugwRI-8ELQe0" tabindex="0" target="_self">
                                 <span>
                                  <a class="ember-view" href="/in/joehas/" id="ember677">
                                   <!-- -->
                                   Joe Haslam
                                   <!-- -->
                                  </a>
                                 </span>
                                </a>
                                <span class="white-space-pre">
                                </span>
                                gave outstanding talks on entrepreneurship in Spain. It has also been amazing exploring and learning more about the history, culture, and cuisine of Madrid and Toledo, where our day trip took us today.
                                <span class="white-space-pre">
                                </span>
                                <a class="RFNOFVQEFZPHaKoCyqsqedOluNQlOEMFjaDeg" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/ACoAABAql74BRhAOQLZuOpjgUo9hmkqKnnndqN0" tabindex="0" target="_self">
                                 <span>
                                  <a class="ember-view" href="/in/loritrudell/" id="ember678">
                                   <!-- -->
                                   Lori Tribble Trudell
                                   <!-- -->
                                  </a>
                                 </span>
                                </a>
                                <span class="white-space-pre">
                                </span>
                                will be posting some of our group photos from Toledo.

                                </span>

                               <span dir="ltr">
                                <!-- -->
                                Clemsons Entrepreneurship and Family Business in Spain study abroad program is in full swing! What an amazing start in Sevilla with our welcome dinner, learning from
                                <span class="white-space-pre">
                                </span>
                                <a class="RFNOFVQEFZPHaKoCyqsqedOluNQlOEMFjaDeg" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/ACoAAComtG4BoBMFgbxzsSyoyVopWrUZ3o96vBY" tabindex="0" target="_self">

                                </span>
                                with
                                <span class="white-space-pre">
                                </span>
                                <a class="RFNOFVQEFZPHaKoCyqsqedOluNQlOEMFjaDeg" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/company/la-fabrica-de-sevilla/" tabindex="0" target="_self">
                                 <span>
                                  <span>
                                   <!-- -->
                                   La Fbrica de Sevilla
                                   <!-- -->
                                  </span>
                                 </span>
                                </a>
                                <span class="white-space-pre">
                                </span>
                                about the awesome things their Chamber of Commerce is doing to support the regions entrepreneurship ecosystem, and a day trip to the Tio Pepe winery in Jerez to learn about their operations, 180-year old family business, and special Sherry wine.
                                <span class="white-space-pre">
                                </span>
                                <a class="RFNOFVQEFZPHaKoCyqsqedOluNQlOEMFjaDeg" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/ACoAABAmtn0B0-5MfP-ZFN_2S4D_jtYchYDdKqI" tabindex="0" target="_self">

                               <span dir="ltr">
                                <!-- -->
                                Hello LinkedIn entrepreneurial investors! As some of you know I am on a mission to gain a better understanding of how and why investors choose to invest in various entrepreneurial ventures. As a PhD candidate at Clemson University studying entrepreneurship, this interest is a perfect fit. I come to you all today - especially entrepreneurial investors - asking a little help....I am in the midst of dominating a really cool dissertation so I can graduate and continue to serve the entrepreneurial community with my PhD; however I NEED the help of investors. No, I don't need any money, rather I would welcome 5-6 minutes of your time to complete this fully anonymous survey which helps us gain a better understanding of how investors make decisions. Here's the anonymous survey link:
                                <span class="white-space-pre">
                                </span>
                                <a class="RFNOFVQEFZPHaKoCyqsqedOluNQlOEMFjaDeg" data-test-app-aware-link="" href="https://lnkd.in/gH2cYX2k" tabindex="0" target="_self">
                                 <!-- -->
                                 https://lnkd.in/gH2cYX2k
                                 <!-- -->
                                </a>
                                <!-- -->
                                . If you're an investor and could take a few minutes to help me out it would be much appreciated!
                                <!-- -->

                             <div class="update-components-text relative update-components-update-v2__commentary" dir="ltr">
                              <!-- -->
                              <span class="break-words tvm-parent-container">
                               <!-- -->
                               <span dir="ltr">
                                <!-- -->
                                Can early-stage entrepreneurship be distilled down to a few core principles?
                                <span class="white-space-pre">
                                </span>
                                <span>
                                 <br/>
                                </span>
                                <!-- -->
                                I wrote this as an introduction to an entrepreneurship class that I teach, and I decided to share it here. It is too long for a LinkedIn post, but the key principles are shared in the first few paragraphs for those who want a quick snapshot without reading to the end.
                                <span class="white-space-pre">
                                </span>
                                <span>
                                 <br/>
                                </span>
                                <!-- -->
                                If you have any thoughts, reactions, or additional insights please let me know.
